00:15:28.750 --> 00:15:32.829
So this is a bad sign; you give a talk, they
don't listen to a thing you say, they've got

00:15:32.829 --> 00:15:37.150
the first question right out of the gates.
So, "Yes sir, you in the back." "Well it's

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:40.839
not a question, it's a comment." That's the
second bad sign, he doesn't have a question,

00:15:40.839 --> 00:15:41.839
he has something to say, [laughs]

00:15:41.839 --> 00:15:42.839
[laughter]

00:15:42.839 --> 00:15:46.579
and he wasn't listening in the first place.
A third bad sign. I say, "Yeah, what's the

00:15:46.579 --> 00:15:49.440
comment?" "Well my, we're, we're on to you."

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:50.440
[pause]

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:52.290
Umm; a tough start to the book tour.

00:15:52.290 --> 00:15:53.870
[laughter]

00:15:53.870 --> 00:16:00.070
"Yes, and what is it? What have you figured
out?" [laughs] He said, "Well, we've been

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:06.449
perusing your book and you're basically using
bumper stickers as the sugar on top to actually

00:16:06.449 --> 00:16:07.800
get us to read about philosophy."

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:08.950
[pause]

00:16:08.950 --> 00:16:16.050
"Wow, that's the sugar on top analogy is really
apt. Oh, kind of wish I'd thought of that."

00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:17.050
[laughter]

00:16:17.050 --> 00:16:21.699
"That's exactly what I'm doing. Is that, have
I been saying something like" - and I thought,

00:16:21.699 --> 00:16:26.880
"Well", my tail is starting to tuck between
my legs and I said, "Yeah, yes. Yes. That's

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:30.139
what I'm, that's what the book is about."
And he said, "Well it's great. We love it."

00:16:30.139 --> 00:16:33.800
I said, "Oh yeah, this is a great book. I'm
very proud of that and that's exactly what's

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:43.339
going on here is that we're using bumper stickers
to get people engaged and to, to really feel

00:16:43.339 --> 00:16:49.230
like they can discuss these philosophical
issues in a way that's relevant to us."

00:16:49.230 --> 00:16:53.699
Because that's, I think, the real power and
beauty of these ideas is that they're not

00:16:53.699 --> 00:16:59.130
merely these abstract notions given to us
by sort of the, the tall ivory towers of academia.

00:16:59.130 --> 00:17:03.020
That's certainly being done and there's a
lot of what's being written and discussed

00:17:03.020 --> 00:17:08.739
in, in academics that is extremely almost
unnecessarily abstract, but the bulk of philosophical

00:17:08.739 --> 00:17:14.109
discourse is extremely relevant and accessible
and I've just, I'd come to find that these

00:17:14.109 --> 00:17:17.329
bumper stickers, bless all of you, were a
great way to go about doing this.

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:23.909
And so in this book proposal that I sent to
Random House it included ten entries [ ]; along

00:17:23.909 --> 00:17:29.549
with the proposal you include a sample of
the writing. And when they wrote back and

00:17:29.549 --> 00:17:35.200
said, "We wanna do this" they said "What we
don't want is the, the guy who wrote these

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:39.889
five entries." And if, if you've seen the
book there are about 160 bumper stickers and

00:17:39.889 --> 00:17:43.989
in a page and a half to two pages, I distill
sort of the deeper meaning behind them, and

00:17:43.989 --> 00:17:45.059
many cases lack thereof.

00:17:45.059 --> 00:17:49.899
And they said, "We don't want these five."
And I said, "What, what didn't you like about

00:17:49.899 --> 00:17:54.979
those five?" "We, we felt like we were reading
a book by a philosophy professor," which is

00:17:54.979 --> 00:17:59.580
what my first two books kind of were. The
second book is blatantly a, a university textbook

00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:05.749
which followed this novel that, that the characters
in the novel sort of living out these philosophical

00:18:05.749 --> 00:18:07.879
ideas, but it's heavily rooted in philosophy.

00:18:07.879 --> 00:18:12.899
And then the second book, it's an 800 page
philosophy textbook. Note to self, "don't

00:18:12.899 --> 00:18:19.269
write any more textbooks". I even have gotten,
I won't call it hate mail, but strong emails

00:18:19.269 --> 00:18:24.131
on my book account after 'The Dream Weaver'
came out and it said, "What's wrong with you?

00:18:24.131 --> 00:18:25.250
This book sucks.

00:18:25.250 --> 00:18:26.250
[laughter]

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:30.799
Like are you depressed?" And I wrote back,
"It's a textbook, like why are you buying

00:18:30.799 --> 00:18:32.279
a philosophy textbook?"

00:18:32.279 --> 00:18:37.029
So I, I have to warn my publisher says, "Don't
fly around the world and tell people not to

00:18:37.029 --> 00:18:40.799
buy your books." I'm telling you right now
the second, don't buy it, the second book.

00:18:40.799 --> 00:18:44.220
I just, I don't wanna deal with the mail that
you're gonna be sending me.

00:18:44.220 --> 00:18:45.220
[laughter]

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:50.570
So those two books were, were very serious
and this one much more playful that we're

00:18:50.570 --> 00:18:57.509
inserting sort of pop culture and things that
are really in, in, in our daily lives into

00:18:57.509 --> 00:19:03.769
these and then, and then allowing us to spend
a paragraph or two paragraphs actually understanding

00:19:03.769 --> 00:19:06.399
and being able to connect with these big ideas.

00:19:06.399 --> 00:19:11.999
So one of those that I'd like to share with
you, and if you have your reading is fun books

00:19:11.999 --> 00:19:13.720
this is on page -

00:19:13.720 --> 00:19:18.179
[sound of pages turning]

00:19:18.179 --> 00:19:21.399
45.

00:19:21.399 --> 00:19:26.450
There's an image, many of the bumper stickers
have images next to them, this has the image

00:19:26.450 --> 00:19:36.190
of a, a, a baby bottle and one of the things
that, that I included in this sticker is an

00:19:36.190 --> 00:19:42.330
idea from a philosopher from Peter Singer
who's a, one of the most well-known living

00:19:42.330 --> 00:19:46.120
philosophers; somewhat controversial, but
he has this great image of being part of a

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:52.279
global village and he uses that to drive home
his sort of utilitarian calculus of morality.

00:19:52.279 --> 00:19:57.570
And he doesn't use it to talk about this topic
per se, but he does weigh in on this topic

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:58.619
a little bit later.

00:19:58.619 --> 00:20:03.190
So I found that this was a great example of,
and this is one of the original five. Random

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:07.799
House didn't like these five and they liked
these five. This is one of their original

00:20:07.799 --> 00:20:11.940
five where they came away saying, "Hey, we've
heard of Peter Singer and his global village.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:17.009
We never really got it until now and by the
way we now react differently towards bottled

00:20:17.009 --> 00:20:18.009
water."

00:20:18.009 --> 00:20:22.330
So the bumper sticker is: "Bottled water is
for suckers."

00:20:22.330 --> 00:20:24.809
[pause]

00:20:24.809 --> 00:20:30.200
"Nowhere in history does the phrase 'selling
ice to Eskimos' apply more aptly than to the

00:20:30.200 --> 00:20:34.679
bottled water fiasco, and not just because
the analog to ice in this case is its melted

00:20:34.679 --> 00:20:41.900
counterpart. We Eskimos have been duped. 'There's
gold in them thar hills' came the cry in the

00:20:41.900 --> 00:20:47.840
1980s. Blue gold. Wait you're going to put
dirtier, less palatable water in a bottle

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:52.289
and ship it around the world to sell?' pausing
between sips of tap water, 'to people that

00:20:52.289 --> 00:20:57.210
already get it for free?' 'Well if they're
willing to spend billions of dollars each

00:20:57.210 --> 00:21:02.830
year on phone psychics, this will be even
easier. We'll even name our first bottling

00:21:02.830 --> 00:21:07.190
'Naïve'. Or maybe we should spell it backward
just to slip it by the consumer; take the

00:21:07.190 --> 00:21:11.490
weird little dots off the 'i'. Evian still
has a nice ring to it. We'll put a picture

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:12.799
of a mountain on it.'

00:21:12.799 --> 00:21:13.799
[laughter]

00:21:13.799 --> 00:21:17.919
If this week in America is like the week before
and the week before that, then we drank a

00:21:17.919 --> 00:21:21.519
billion bottles of water and we'll drink another
billion next week.

00:21:21.519 --> 00:21:25.809
In a time of great financial struggle and
concern for our planet's survival this life

00:21:25.809 --> 00:21:32.279
force must be cleaner and better tasting.
Right? Most blind taste tests actually show

00:21:32.279 --> 00:21:37.259
the palatability of tap water. This should
be of no surprise as tap water is more highly

00:21:37.259 --> 00:21:42.740
regulated. Even in our more high brow case
of wine tasting, expert oenophiles, fancy

00:21:42.740 --> 00:21:47.739
name for wine snobs, are easily tricked into
thinking a white wine with red food coloring

00:21:47.739 --> 00:21:53.019
is actually red wine, or that a bottle, or
that wine from a 90 dollar bottle tastes better

00:21:53.019 --> 00:21:56.989
than the same wine in a bottle with 10 dollars
on it.

00:21:56.989 --> 00:22:02.489
Okay, so humans are gullible; they form pre-conceived
notions; what's the harm?

00:22:02.489 --> 00:22:07.460
For you, the consumer, the only harms are
you're drinking a less regulated product at

00:22:07.460 --> 00:22:12.330
greater cost. For you, the environment, the
only harms are the massive fuel and emissions

00:22:12.330 --> 00:22:16.129
required to ship this heavy substance around
the world and all the bottles left to deal

00:22:16.129 --> 00:22:20.570
with. For you, one of the billion who don't
have access to safe drinking water, you're

00:22:20.570 --> 00:22:22.919
probably not reading this book.

00:22:22.919 --> 00:22:27.149
To further illustrate, Princeton University
ethicist, Peter Singer, uses the concept of

00:22:27.149 --> 00:22:33.309
a global village. He suggests that we have
a moral duty to all of the members of our

00:22:33.309 --> 00:22:38.909
village, even if we don't see them, and especially
if we can do so without sacrificing anything

00:22:38.909 --> 00:22:44.299
of comparable moral, comparable moral importance,
as in his clear cut example in which we should

00:22:44.299 --> 00:22:48.470
muddy our pants if it saves the life of a
drowning child.

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:54.169
A quick trip to Fiji provides a perfect application.
Due to the country's isolation and volcanic

00:22:54.169 --> 00:22:58.869
soil, much of their population cannot get
safe drinking water. The Fiji Company boasts

00:22:58.869 --> 00:23:03.429
of this on their Website. 'Fiji is far away,
but when it comes to drinking water remote

00:23:03.429 --> 00:23:05.539
happens to be very, very good.'

00:23:05.539 --> 00:23:10.789
So they paint a hibiscus flower on every bottle
and ship it ten thousand miles to San Francisco

00:23:10.789 --> 00:23:15.460
where someone sits in a bath of perfectly
safe drinking water straight from the springs

00:23:15.460 --> 00:23:18.440
of Yosemite, sipping Fiji.

00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:22.849
Little does our bather know there is likely
more fecal matter in the bottle than in the

00:23:22.849 --> 00:23:28.889
tub. Fiji water has three times the colony
forming units for E. coli, the bacteria found

00:23:28.889 --> 00:23:32.429
in human feces, than the recommended maximum.

00:23:32.429 --> 00:23:37.070
As other bumper sticker wisdom reminds us,
'shit happens,' but who'd of thunk it happens

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:40.211
in our now strangely nutty tasting premium
bottled water?

00:23:40.211 --> 00:23:41.480
[laughter]

00:23:41.480 --> 00:23:47.399
So in light of the thousands in our global
village who die daily from diseases transmitted

00:23:47.399 --> 00:23:53.460
through contaminated water, Singer suggests
we instead 'put that dollar in a jar, carry

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:57.799
a water bottle, send all the money to someone
who has real needs and you're no worse off.'

00:23:57.799 --> 00:24:02.919
It's funny in that not so funny way, that
we'll drive ten minutes out of our way to

00:24:02.919 --> 00:24:07.479
buy 15 gallons of gas for 20 cents cheaper
per gallon and then walk in the gas mart and

00:24:07.479 --> 00:24:11.070
plunk down 3 dollars for something we get
for free. Sucker."

00:24:11.070 --> 00:24:13.320
[laughter]

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:18.919
So, there we have a, a very good example,
and none of these in any way follow templates

00:24:18.919 --> 00:24:23.100
or formulas. I mean that was sort of the fun
of writing the book. Sometimes the pop culture

00:24:23.100 --> 00:24:27.139
sneaks in at the end; sometimes we don't have
direct quotes from philosophers; sometimes

00:24:27.139 --> 00:24:32.249
it's a little heavier on the philosophy with
some of the more serious topics. But the idea

00:24:32.249 --> 00:24:37.029
being that we have the, the bumper stickers
serving as the sugar on top; that the Oracle

00:24:37.029 --> 00:24:42.859
guy is so in my head. We have the sugar on
top; we have something in pop culture that

00:24:42.859 --> 00:24:48.840
we connect with; and then we get sort of one
or two of these big ideas from big thinkers

00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:50.269
and can tie it all together.

00:24:50.269 --> 00:24:53.389
So one of the other ones and I'll paraphrase
a few and then have one I'd like to finish

00:24:53.389 --> 00:25:00.159
with, that Random House liked is the bumper
sticker: "Size does matter" typically on a

00:25:00.159 --> 00:25:01.759
Hummer.

00:25:01.759 --> 00:25:07.349
And what this allowed me to do, I went and
looked at the cup sizes from fast food chains

00:25:07.349 --> 00:25:14.100
and found that in almost exactly 10 years,
the large of 10 years ago, the exact same

00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:19.719
size cup is now small, and they go up from
there. And some don't even offer small anymore,

00:25:19.719 --> 00:25:23.479
they just start with medium or Starbucks has
that creepy tall that's like the smallest

00:25:23.479 --> 00:25:29.549
is a tall. So we can sort of start to look
at this relativity of size. How can the same

00:25:29.549 --> 00:25:33.249
size cup be both large and small?

00:25:33.249 --> 00:25:41.009
So then 7-11 comes along, gives us the Big
Gulp; 32 ounces of this carbonated elixir.

00:25:41.009 --> 00:25:48.169
Now the, the human stomach is on average 30
to 34 ounces. So the Big Gulp fills an empty

00:25:48.169 --> 00:25:51.289
human stomach with soda.

00:25:51.289 --> 00:25:56.629
Now about three years later they perform what
I and my philosophical mindset consider to

00:25:56.629 --> 00:26:04.399
be metaphysical magic; they turned the Big
Gulp without even touching it into just Gulp;

00:26:04.399 --> 00:26:07.760
with the Super Gulp, 64 ounces.

00:26:07.760 --> 00:26:08.869
[laughter]

00:26:08.869 --> 00:26:12.870
Now on the West Coast I realize we didn't
have this on the East Coast. The West Coast

00:26:12.870 --> 00:26:20.840
I have to actually brace myself here a little
bit. Arco has given us a handle on each side,

00:26:20.840 --> 00:26:21.840
The Beast.

00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:22.940
[laughter]

00:26:22.940 --> 00:26:27.669
Eighty-eight ounces; you can't drink it in
under 45 minutes or your body will expel -

00:26:27.669 --> 00:26:28.669
[laughter]

00:26:28.669 --> 00:26:29.749
the liquid.

00:26:29.749 --> 00:26:34.529
So we have this inroad with everybody kind
of looking at the relativity of size, and

00:26:34.529 --> 00:26:39.080
I'm not sure if we saw three weeks ago in
the New York Times there was an article on

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:43.629
the, the Last Supper, the rendition of the
Last Supper and how it's been reproduced over

00:26:43.629 --> 00:26:48.940
the years. And as it's been reproduced over
the years, the food portions have grown 47

00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:53.200
percent. They saw this is clearly isn't enough
bread to feed all these guys, so the food

00:26:53.200 --> 00:26:54.200
has grown.

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:55.200
[laughter]

00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:58.430
So we're sort of looking at the relativity
of size and we've got this bumper sticker

00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:02.769
to frame it and talk about like size does
matter, but the question is in what way does

00:27:02.769 --> 00:27:07.970
it matter? And it now allows us this inroads
to this fascinating discussion that was going

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:12.320
on between Philosopher Gott, Gottfried Leibniz
and Sir Isaac Newton.

00:27:12.320 --> 00:27:17.749
Now Leibniz was actually arguing on behalf
of what we've seen here; the relativity of

00:27:17.749 --> 00:27:21.909
size. That it's not so much the intrinsic
size of the object, but the, the size of things

00:27:21.909 --> 00:27:25.850
relative to it and he gives a couple of really
engaging thought experiments to drive that

00:27:25.850 --> 00:27:26.850
home.

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:30.769
Newton, on the other hand, was arguing that
sort of the more intuitive position that the,

00:27:30.769 --> 00:27:35.519
the intrinsic size of the object is what matters
regardless of what's next to it or over time.

00:27:35.519 --> 00:27:43.759
And then along comes Einstein relativity theory
and as Barbara said at Random House, "I finally

00:27:43.759 --> 00:27:46.999
understood relativity theory. I didn't get
it from1 Stephen Hawking's book," (which I

00:27:46.999 --> 00:27:51.009
think is actually very eloquent) "but I got
it from this, because you were able to sort

00:27:51.009 --> 00:27:54.859
of frame it in this way that's made more relevant
to us."

00:27:54.859 --> 00:28:01.609
So again that's, that's sort of the, the overall
approach to how I went about writing, writing

00:28:01.609 --> 00:28:06.580
the book, is that I'm basically, I'm, I'm
trying to share the excitement that I had

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:12.450
initially when I left; really nice introduction
mentioned that I was a human biology major

00:28:12.450 --> 00:28:16.619
and headed to med school. I was actually about
a month away from med school. I'd gotten in

00:28:16.619 --> 00:28:23.419
and found this philosophy book. It's blue
and white bound actually written by the philosopher,

00:28:23.419 --> 00:28:28.330
philosophy professor at Stanford who does
NPR's philosophy talk and then sort of serendipitously

00:28:28.330 --> 00:28:33.519
all comes back full circle and blurbed this
book. Sort of it's all his fault in, in the

00:28:33.519 --> 00:28:35.619
good way that I'm here today.

00:28:35.619 --> 00:28:42.469
And it steered me away and I called my parents
and I said, "Hey, thanks for that great education.

00:28:42.469 --> 00:28:46.440
By the way, I'm going to get a degree in philosophy
instead." Like, "we'll be in touch."

00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:47.440
[laughter]

00:28:47.440 --> 00:28:52.129
And, and I was trying to share all of these
ideas with family and friends and their responses

00:28:52.129 --> 00:28:56.029
were typically, "I don't understand what you're
saying," or "I don't really see how that's

00:28:56.029 --> 00:29:00.909
relevant in my life." And it was the exact
opposite experience that I was having. And

00:29:00.909 --> 00:29:05.719
I found that 12 years later, two books later,
umpteen number of courses and classes later,

00:29:05.719 --> 00:29:10.590
this is by far the best way that I could figure
out how to get these ideas out and get people

00:29:10.590 --> 00:29:11.929
engaged in talking.

00:29:11.929 --> 00:29:17.499
And one of the best reviews that I've gotten
was actually at a book club two nights ago

00:29:17.499 --> 00:29:23.070
who read this book and one of the women there
said, "My son and I have been reading this

00:29:23.070 --> 00:29:26.789
book and just the other day we were driving
around and he saw a bumper sticker and" (she

00:29:26.789 --> 00:29:30.230
says this has happened a lot; the one that
she referenced was "Jesus is coming, look

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:31.230
busy."

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:32.230
[laughter]

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:37.950
But what he did is he said, "Hey, Mom look
at that bumper sticker. Now what is the difference

00:29:37.950 --> 00:29:42.100
between sort of Christianity and Judaism?"
And they had this discussion about like what

00:29:42.100 --> 00:29:45.460
they should be doing with their lives; they
weren't very religious; since they were sort

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:49.919
of talking about these ideas through the bumper
sticker, and she said it was the best discussion

00:29:49.919 --> 00:29:55.359
she's ever had with her son because they were
open to this notion that these bumper sticker

00:29:55.359 --> 00:29:57.960
slogans had something real behind them.

00:29:57.960 --> 00:30:03.729
And I mean that's exactly what I wanted to
hear. A bumper sticker and eight words doesn't

00:30:03.729 --> 00:30:09.279
capture the depths of these big ideas. Charles
Schultz, the creator of the Peanuts cartoon

00:30:09.279 --> 00:30:13.679
once said, you might have seen it on the music
video, "There's a difference between a philosophy

00:30:13.679 --> 00:30:18.469
and a bumper sticker." Absolutely; let's hope
so. I mean I think the problem and why many

00:30:18.469 --> 00:30:23.950
of these bumper sticker slogans seem so antagonistic
is that they're, they're monologues. When

00:30:23.950 --> 00:30:28.509
someone yells, basically yells at you from
their bumper and then drives away and you

00:30:28.509 --> 00:30:30.559
don't get to have that discourse.

00:30:30.559 --> 00:30:36.080
And so what I, what I did was had that discourse
for two pages, and then what I love to hear

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:42.409
from readers is and then we had discourse
for another hour over a cup of coffee or beer

00:30:42.409 --> 00:30:45.580
or whatnot; that it's used as sort of that
springboard.

00:30:45.580 --> 00:30:52.389
So to get to the, the final reading, one of
the questions that comes up a lot so I'm just

00:30:52.389 --> 00:30:58.809
